            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the shop floor display: kiosk mode, authentication, worker cards, job actions, receiving, shipping, and stage filtering.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"sf1","text":"You're setting up a new shop floor kiosk. After opening the display, what is the primary way workers authenticate to perform actions?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They log in with their email and password through the standard login page"},{"id":"b","text":"They scan their RFID badge or barcode and enter their numeric PIN","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"An admin logs them in from the admin panel"},{"id":"d","text":"They use a shared kiosk password posted on the wall"}],"explanation":"The shop floor display uses ephemeral scan-based authentication. Workers scan their RFID badge or barcode, then enter their numeric PIN (minimum 4 digits). The session is automatically cleared after the action is complete. Alternatively, workers can tap their name card and enter their full password."},{"id":"sf2","text":"A worker scans their badge at the shop floor kiosk but walks away without entering their PIN. What happens after 20 seconds?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The system sends a notification to the worker's phone"},{"id":"b","text":"The PIN overlay stays open indefinitely until someone cancels it"},{"id":"c","text":"The PIN overlay auto-cancels and the display returns to the main dashboard","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"The worker is automatically clocked out"}],"explanation":"The PIN phase has a 20-second auto-dismiss timeout. If the worker doesn't submit within that time, the overlay cancels automatically and the display returns to the main dashboard. This prevents stale overlays from blocking the kiosk for other workers."},{"id":"sf3","text":"On the worker card grid, what does a yellow left stripe on a worker's card indicate?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The worker is currently working on a job"},{"id":"b","text":"The worker is on break or lunch","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worker is clocked out for the day"},{"id":"d","text":"The worker has an overdue job assignment"}],"explanation":"The left stripe color indicates the worker's clock status: green means working, yellow means on break or lunch, and gray means clocked out. The colors are determined by the ClockEventTypeService status mapping."},{"id":"sf4","text":"A worker clocks in but has no assigned jobs. What happens next on the shop floor display?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the worker sees the standard actions overlay and can log out"},{"id":"b","text":"A job picker overlay appears automatically, showing unassigned jobs the worker can select","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worker is redirected to the kanban board to find a job"},{"id":"d","text":"An alert is sent to the manager to assign a job"}],"explanation":"After clocking in, if the worker has no assigned jobs, a job selection overlay appears automatically (after a brief 0.8-second feedback delay). The worker can pick an unassigned job or skip. The overlay has a 15-second auto-dismiss timeout."},{"id":"sf5","text":"How do you assign an unassigned job to a worker directly from the shop floor main dashboard (without authenticating)?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Click the unassigned job, then click the worker's name from a dropdown"},{"id":"b","text":"Drag the unassigned job card from the unassigned section and drop it onto the worker's card","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Right-click the job and select 'Assign To'"},{"id":"d","text":"You cannot assign jobs from the main dashboard — you must authenticate first"}],"explanation":"Unassigned job cards are draggable. Drag a job from the unassigned jobs section and drop it onto any worker card in the grid. The assignment is made immediately via the API, and the display refreshes. No authentication is required for drag-and-drop assignment."},{"id":"sf6","text":"A Production Worker authenticates on the shop floor kiosk. Which dock actions will they see?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Both Receive Goods and Ship Goods"},{"id":"b","text":"Receive Goods only","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Ship Goods only"},{"id":"d","text":"Neither — dock actions are only for Admin users"}],"explanation":"Receive Goods is available to Admin, Manager, OfficeManager, Engineer, and ProductionWorker roles. Ship Goods is restricted to Admin, Manager, and OfficeManager roles only. Both require the worker to be actively clocked in."},{"id":"sf7","text":"You adjust the font size on the shop floor kiosk to 18px and switch to dark theme. The browser is restarted. What happens to these settings?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They reset to defaults (12px, light theme)"},{"id":"b","text":"They are preserved — font size and theme are saved to localStorage","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only the theme is preserved, font size resets"},{"id":"d","text":"They are saved to the user's account preferences on the server"}],"explanation":"Both font size (stored as 'sf-font-index' in localStorage) and theme (stored as 'sf-theme' in localStorage) persist across browser restarts. This ensures the kiosk retains its display settings without reconfiguration."},{"id":"sf8","text":"What does the IsShopFloor flag on a job stage control?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether jobs in that stage can be edited from the shop floor"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether jobs in that stage appear on the shop floor display","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Whether workers can clock in when assigned to jobs in that stage"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the stage column is visible on the kanban board"}],"explanation":"The IsShopFloor boolean flag on TrackType and JobStage entities controls visibility on the shop floor display. Only stages with IsShopFloor = true show their jobs. This filters out non-physical stages like quoting, invoicing, and payment that are irrelevant to production floor workers."},{"id":"sf9","text":"During the receiving flow on the shop floor, a worker selects a purchase order. What can they adjust before confirming receipt?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor name and PO number"},{"id":"b","text":"The quantity to receive for each line item and optionally select a bin location","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The unit price and total cost of each line"},{"id":"d","text":"The expected delivery date and carrier information"}],"explanation":"The receiving overlay shows each PO line with its remaining quantity. Workers adjust the receive quantity per line using +/- buttons (capped at the remaining quantity). They can also optionally select a bin location from a dropdown. Clicking 'Receive All' submits all lines with quantity > 0."},{"id":"sf10","text":"A worker starts a timer on a job from the shop floor actions overlay. Where does this timer show up?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only in the Time Tracking page — the shop floor display does not show active timers"},{"id":"b","text":"On the worker's card in the main grid, as a timer icon next to the job, and the job row is highlighted in the actions overlay","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only in the header stats bar as a global timer count"},{"id":"d","text":"In a separate timer panel that slides out from the right"}],"explanation":"Active timers are visible in multiple places on the shop floor: the worker's card shows a timer icon (timer) next to the job with an active timer, and the job row in the actions overlay gets an active highlight (sf-actions-card__job--active). The timer is started via POST /time-tracking/timer/start and can be stopped from the same overlay."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Inventory Scan Station (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Inventory Scan Station",
            Slug = "shop-floor-scan-station",
            Summary = "The barcode-driven Inventory Scan hub: scan a part to open the 8-action overlay (Move, Count, Receive, Issue, Ship, Inspect, Job, Return), multi-scan mode, and how the same overlay fires on the main display.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/scan"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","scan","inventory"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Inventory Scan Station\n\nThe Inventory Scan Station is a dedicated, barcode-first kiosk page at `/display/shop-floor/scan`. It is built for warehouse and stockroom staff who work mostly with a handheld scanner: scan a part, choose what to do, confirm, repeat. There is no menu to navigate — the part you scan determines what actions are offered.\n\n### Scan to Begin\n\nThe page shows a single large prompt — 'Scan a part barcode to begin' — and a focused scan input. Scan a part's barcode (or type the part number and press Enter) and the system looks up that part. The header keeps a running 'Scanned' counter for the session, and a **Recent Scans** list builds up below the input showing each part you have looked at, its description, and its current stock — so you can see at a glance what you have been working through.\n\nWhen a part is found, the **scan action overlay** opens. If the barcode is not recognized, you get a 'Part not found' message and the overlay closes after a moment so you can scan the next item.\n\n### The Action Overlay — Part Context\n\nThe top of the overlay confirms what you scanned: the part number, description, a stock badge showing the current on-hand quantity, and the current location (when the part lives in a single known bin). This is your sanity check before you act — make sure the part and stock match what is in your hand.\n\n### The 8 Actions\n\nBelow the part context is a grid of large, touch-friendly action buttons. The system only offers the actions that make sense for that part right now; actions that do not apply are shown disabled with a short reason (for example, **Ship** is disabled when the part has no open shipment lines). The eight actions are:\n\n- **Move** (swap_horiz) — relocate stock from one bin to another. You pick the from-location, the to-location, and the quantity.\n- **Count** (inventory) — perform a cycle count for a bin: enter the actual quantity you physically counted, and the system records the variance against what it expected.\n- **Receive** (move_to_inbox) — receive incoming stock against an open purchase-order line, into a chosen bin.\n- **Issue** (output) — issue material to a job: pick the job, the from-location, and the quantity consumed.\n- **Ship** (local_shipping) — fulfill an open shipment line for this part (only enabled when the part has open shipment lines).\n- **Inspect** (fact_check) — run a quality inspection against the part's QC template.\n- **Job** (engineering) — when you scan a job barcode instead of a part, the overlay surfaces job context (number, title, stage, assignee, timer state) and job actions.\n- **Return** (assignment_return) — record a return against a recent shipment of this part (only enabled when recent shipments exist).\n\nTap an action and a short guided flow takes over inside the overlay, collecting just the fields that action needs (quantities, locations, the target job/PO/shipment). Each flow has its own Confirm and Cancel — Cancel drops you back to the action grid without changing anything.\n\n### Multi-Scan Mode\n\nFor repetitive work — receiving a pallet, moving a whole shelf — turn on **Multi-Scan** (the repeat toggle in the overlay footer). With multi-scan on, completing an action does not close the overlay; instead it returns to the action grid and shows 'Ready for next scan', so you can immediately scan the next part and keep going. With multi-scan off (the default), the overlay closes after each completed action and returns you to the scan prompt. Tap **Done** at any time to close the overlay.\n\n### The Same Overlay on the Main Display\n\nYou do not have to be on the dedicated scan page to use these actions. The main shop floor display (`/display/shop-floor`) embeds the very same scan action overlay. When a part barcode is scanned on the main display, the overlay pops up there too, with the identical 8-action grid and flows. The dedicated `/scan` page simply gives stockroom staff a clean, full-screen home for this workflow without the worker-card grid around it.\n\n### What Gets Recorded\n\nEvery completed scan action writes a movement and a scan-log entry: the part, quantity, from/to locations, the related job/PO/shipment, who did it, and when. That log powers both the **Daily Scan Log** (a filterable record of the day's activity) and the **Reverse/Undo** panel (which lets a supervisor back out a recent mistake). See the Field Reference for those two surfaces.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Inventory Scan Station (Walkthrough) ─────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Inventory Scan Station — Guided Tour",
            Slug = "shop-floor-scan-station-walkthrough",
            Summary = "A guided tour of the dedicated Inventory Scan page: the scan prompt, the focused scan input, the running scan counter, and the Recent Scans list.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/scan"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","scan","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/display/shop-floor/scan","startButtonLabel":"Tour the Scan Station","steps":[{"element":".inv-scan__header","popover":{"title":"Scan Station Header","description":"This is the dedicated Inventory Scan page. The header shows the page title and a running 'Scanned' counter that tracks how many parts you have looked up this session.","side":"bottom"},"side":"bottom"},{"element":".inv-scan__cta","popover":{"title":"Scan to Begin","description":"The big prompt tells you the page is waiting for input. Just scan a part barcode (or a storage-location or job barcode) to start — the part you scan decides which actions are offered.","side":"bottom"},"side":"bottom"},{"element":".inv-scan__input-area","popover":{"title":"Focused Scan Input","description":"This input stays focused so a handheld scanner's keystrokes land here automatically. You can also type a part number and press Enter. When a part is found, the action overlay opens with up to 8 actions (Move, Count, Receive, Issue, Ship, Inspect, Job, Return).","side":"top"},"side":"top"},{"element":".inv-scan__input-area","popover":{"title":"Multi-Scan for Repetitive Work","description":"Inside the overlay, turn on Multi-Scan to keep it open after each action so you can scan the next part immediately — ideal for receiving a pallet or moving a whole shelf. With it off, the overlay closes after each completed action and returns here.","side":"top"},"side":"top"},{"element":".inv-scan__body","popover":{"title":"Recent Scans","description":"As you scan, a Recent Scans list builds up here showing each part number, description, and its current stock — a quick record of what you have worked through this session.","side":"top"},"side":"top"}]}"""
        });

        // ── Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk (Article) ──────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk",
            Slug = "shop-floor-kiosk-setup",
            Summary = "First-time terminal pairing: an admin signs in, names the terminal, picks or creates a team, and the device gets a persistent token — gating both the main display and the clock kiosk.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/clock","/display/shop-floor"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","setup","admin","terminal"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk\n\nBefore a shop floor display or clock kiosk can be used, the device has to be **paired** to your install and assigned to a team. This is a one-time setup an administrator does when the kiosk is first opened on a new device. After pairing, ordinary workers use the kiosk without ever logging in as an admin again.\n\n### When Setup Appears\n\nWhen the clock kiosk (`/display/shop-floor/clock`) opens, it checks the browser for a saved **device token** in localStorage. If no token is found — a brand-new device, a cleared browser, or a terminal that was deactivated server-side — the kiosk drops into **Setup** instead of the worker dashboard. Setup has two phases.\n\n### Phase 1 — Admin Sign-In\n\nThe first screen asks an administrator to sign in with their email and password. This is a deliberate gate: only an admin (or a user with the right to manage terminals) can pair a device, so a worker cannot accidentally re-home a kiosk to the wrong team. Bad credentials show an inline 'Invalid admin credentials' error. A successful sign-in loads the list of teams and advances to configuration.\n\n### Phase 2 — Name the Terminal & Choose a Team\n\nNow you give the kiosk an identity:\n\n- **Terminal Name** — a human label for this physical station, e.g. 'Weld Cell Kiosk' or 'Shipping Dock Tablet'. This is how the terminal shows up in the admin's terminal list. It is required.\n- **Team** — pick an existing team from the dropdown (each option shows the team name and its member count), or click **Create New Team**, type a new team name, and it is created on the spot. The team you choose scopes what the kiosk shows: the clock dashboard and worker list are filtered to that team.\n\nClick **Activate Terminal** to finish. Behind the scenes the kiosk generates a device token (a random UUID), saves it to localStorage, registers the terminal + team against the server, and then **clears the admin session** — the admin is intentionally signed out so the kiosk is left in an unauthenticated, worker-ready state.\n\n### What the Token Does\n\nThe device token is the kiosk's persistent identity. On every subsequent open, the kiosk reads the token from localStorage and validates it against the server:\n\n- **Valid** → the kiosk skips setup entirely and goes straight to the team dashboard.\n- **Missing or rejected** (terminal deleted or deactivated by an admin) → the saved token and terminal are cleared and the kiosk returns to Setup, ready to be re-paired.\n\nBecause the token lives in the browser's localStorage, pairing is per-device/per-browser. Re-imaging the machine, switching browsers, or clearing site data will require re-pairing. An admin can also deactivate a terminal from the admin terminal list, which forces that device back into Setup the next time it loads.\n\n### Managing Terminals Later\n\nTerminals are listed and managed on the server side (under the shop floor / kiosk terminal admin). From there an admin can review which physical stations are paired, see their assigned teams, and deactivate a terminal that has been retired or relocated. Deactivating does not touch the device — it simply invalidates the token so the next load re-runs Setup.\n\n### Setup Gates Both Kiosks\n\nThe same pairing protects both kiosk surfaces. The dedicated **clock kiosk** runs setup directly. The **main shop floor display** likewise relies on a configured terminal/team context to show the right workers and jobs. Pair the device once and both surfaces are ready for the floor.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Clock Kiosk (Article) ────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Using the Clock Kiosk",
            Slug = "shop-floor-clock-kiosk",
            Summary = "The dedicated clock-in/out kiosk: the team dashboard, the dual-scan flow (badge or job barcode in any order), PIN entry, the manual-login fallback, and ephemeral auto-logout.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/clock"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","clock","scan"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Using the Clock Kiosk\n\nThe Clock Kiosk at `/display/shop-floor/clock` is a focused, full-screen station for clocking in and out. It is simpler than the main shop floor display — no worker-card grid, no drag-and-drop — and it is built around a single focused scan input so a badge reader (or RFID relay) drives the whole flow. Once a device is paired (see 'Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk'), the kiosk opens straight to its team dashboard.\n\n### The Team Dashboard\n\nThe header shows the kiosk's team (a color dot + team name), a live clock and date, and a kiosk search bar. A KPI strip across the top gives an at-a-glance team picture: how many workers are Working, On Break, and Off, plus Active Jobs, Done Today, and an Overdue count (shown only when there is at least one overdue job). Below that, the dashboard lists the team's workers grouped by status — working, on break, and clocked out — and a list of the team's active jobs. The dashboard refreshes itself every 15 seconds.\n\n### The Dual-Scan Flow\n\nThe defining feature of the clock kiosk is that it accepts **two kinds of scan, in either order**. At the bottom of the dashboard is an always-focused scan input. When something is scanned, the kiosk identifies it:\n\n- **Employee badge** → goes straight to the PIN screen.\n- **Job barcode** → the kiosk shows the scanned job (number, title, stage) and prompts 'Scan your badge to continue'. This lets a worker scan the job they are about to work on first, then their badge — the clock event is tied to that job. Scan order does not matter: badge-then-job or job-then-badge both work.\n- **Unrecognized** → a 'scan not recognized' message on the dashboard.\n\nIf the identify call fails for any reason, the kiosk falls back to treating the scan as an employee badge and shows the PIN screen anyway, so a worker is never blocked from clocking in.\n\n### PIN Entry\n\nAfter a badge is recognized, the worker enters their numeric PIN (minimum 4 digits, up to 8). Any job they scanned first is shown on the PIN card as a reminder. Submitting performs a scan-login: badge + PIN. A wrong badge/PIN shows 'Invalid badge or PIN' and lets them retry; **Back** returns to the dashboard.\n\n### Manual-Login Fallback\n\nSome situations have no working badge — a new hire whose card has not printed, a damaged badge, a visitor covering a shift. The **Clock In Manually** button opens an email + password login. This is the standard credential login (not the kiosk PIN), and it lands the worker in the same clock-action screen as a successful scan. Bad credentials show 'Invalid credentials'.\n\n### The Clock Action Screen\n\nOnce authenticated (by scan+PIN or manual login), the worker sees the available clock actions. The buttons are generated from the clock event type configuration based on each worker's current status — Clock In when they are out, Clock Out / Break / Lunch when they are in, plus any custom event types your install defines. Each button carries its own icon and color. If a job was scanned in the dual-scan flow, it is shown as a banner so the worker can confirm they are clocking against the right job. Tapping an action records the clock event.\n\n### Ephemeral Authentication & Auto-Logout\n\nLike the main display, the clock kiosk uses **ephemeral** auth — there is no lingering login session. The moment a clock action completes, the kiosk clears the session, refreshes the data, and returns to the team dashboard, ready for the next person. A 30-second inactivity timer also auto-logs-out a worker who walks away mid-flow (any button press resets it), so the kiosk never sits unlocked on someone's account. Cancelling out of the PIN, job-scanned, or manual-login screens likewise clears state and returns to the dashboard.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Shop Floor Kiosk — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "shop-floor-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and power-user reference: scanner device pairing, multi-worker sessions, training mode, the WebHID RFID relay, token revocation/re-pairing, and IsShopFloor stage visibility config.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Scanner Device Pairing\n\nBeyond the kiosk-to-team pairing (see \"Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk\"), individual **scanner hardware** can be registered to a terminal from the **Paired Scanners** panel (`scan-devices-panel`). Click **Pair New**, focus the **Device ID** field, and capture the unit's identity, then optionally give it a friendly **Device Name** (e.g. \"Receiving Cart 2\"). Three hardware types are supported:\n\n- **USB Barcode Scanner (keyboard wedge)** — plug into USB, focus the field, scan the device serial barcode on the scanner body (or a reserved test barcode).\n- **NFC Reader (ACR122U + NTAG215)** — plug the ACR122U in (wait for the solid green LED), focus the field, tap a dedicated NTAG215 sticker (one per reader, not a user badge); its UID populates the field.\n- **Wireless / Bluetooth Scanner** — pair to the OS in HID mode first, then focus the field and scan the device serial barcode.\n\nEach paired row shows the device name/ID, **Paired** date, and an **Active / Inactive** badge. **Unpair** (link_off) removes a device. A paired scanner is registered hardware; it is distinct from the live RFID relay connection below.\n\n## Multi-Worker Sessions\n\nThe kiosk is a shared station, so `KioskSessionService` lets several workers hold concurrent in-flight sessions on one device. Sessions persist to an IndexedDB store (`forge-kiosk-sessions`, key `userId`) so they survive a page reload. Exactly one session is **foreground** (`isForeground`) at a time — the worker currently acting; the rest are backgrounded but retain their `mode` (`ScanMode`: move | count | receive | issue | ship | inspect) and `workflowState`, so a worker can resume a half-finished scan flow after someone else steps in.\n\n- **Concurrency cap** — `kiosk:max_concurrent_sessions` (localStorage, default **5**). When a new worker activates beyond the cap, the **oldest by lastActivity** session is evicted.\n- **Idle expiry** — a checker runs every 30s and drops any session idle longer than `kiosk:session_timeout_minutes` (localStorage, default **5** minutes).\n- **Foreground swap** — re-activating an existing user brings their session to the foreground and refreshes `lastActivity`; `backgroundCurrentSession()` parks the current one.\n\nThis is separate from the main display's 30-second actions-overlay auto-logout — that governs a single authenticated overlay, whereas sessions track multiple parked workers.\n\n## Training Mode\n\n`KioskSessionService.isTrainingMode` is a boolean signal (toggled via `enableTrainingMode()` / `disableTrainingMode()`) for practicing the kiosk without committing real transactions. When on, the `TrainingModeBannerComponent` (`app-training-mode-banner`, driven by a `visible` input) shows a persistent banner so no one mistakes a training session for live work.\n\n## WebHID RFID Relay\n\n`WebHidRfidService` is the contactless-badge transport, and it tries two paths in order:\n\n1. **WebSocket relay (preferred, cross-browser)** — connects to a local relay at `ws://localhost:9876`. The relay is a small companion app that talks to the physical reader and forwards `scan` / `connected` / `disconnected` / `error` messages as JSON. It auto-reconnects every 3s unless intentionally closed. If the relay is not reachable, `probeRelay()` sets the error to `rfid.relayNotInstalled` so the UI can prompt to install it.\n2. **WebHID fallback (Chromium only)** — when the relay is absent and `'hid' in navigator`, the service uses `navigator.hid` (`requestDevice()` to pair, `getDevices()` to silently reconnect). It listens for `inputreport` events and extracts the card UID (strips leading/trailing zero padding and an optional length prefix, emits uppercase hex). It also listens for the device `disconnect` event.\n\nWhen multiple readers are reported, the service prefers a contactless/NFC name (matches `contactless|nfc|rfid|acr122`) over a contact/EMV reader. `disconnect()` tears down both transports and removes all listeners.\n\n## Token Revocation & Re-Pairing\n\nA paired kiosk stores its identity as `forge-kiosk-device-token` in localStorage (alongside `forge-kiosk-terminal`). On every load, the clock kiosk validates the token by calling `getTerminal(deviceToken)`:\n\n- **Valid** → the terminal config loads and the kiosk goes straight to its team dashboard.\n- **Not found / deactivated** (an admin retired or reassigned the terminal server-side) → both `forge-kiosk-device-token` and `forge-kiosk-terminal` are removed from localStorage and the kiosk drops back into **Setup**, ready to be re-paired.\n\nSo \"revoking\" a kiosk is a server-side deactivate; the device discovers it on next load and self-clears. Because the token lives in the browser, clearing site data, re-imaging, or switching browsers also forces re-pairing.\n\n## IsShopFloor Stage Visibility Config\n\nThe `IsShopFloor` boolean lives on both the `TrackType` and the `JobStage` entities and is the single switch that controls which kanban stages surface jobs on the shop floor. Only stages with `IsShopFloor = true` display their jobs on the main display and clock kiosk — keeping non-physical stages (Quote Requested, Quoted, Invoiced, Payment Received, etc.) off the floor. Configure it per stage under **Admin → Track Types**; each stage within a track type is toggled individually.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Shop Floor training modules");
    }
}
